Let&#39;s first talk about how you can improve your code.

 1. Don&#39;t duplicate your code. (In this case, use a loop)
 2. Don&#39;t put everything in the constructor.
 3. Give your components (i.e JButtons, JPanel, etc) good names that are easier to remember and not single variables.
 
Belief explanation.

 1. Instead of creating, setting the border, and adding JTextFields to the panel separately. In this case 82 times. Use a ```for``` loop. Avoid duplicate code to keep your code clean and more OO.

        for (int x=0; x&lt;=82; x++){
            JTextField textField = new JTextField(&quot;&quot;,1);
            textField.setBorder(new LineBorder(Color.black, 2));
            field.add(textField);

2. Use a constructor if you want to initialize values for an object or read the doc for more information.

3. Naming your JButton &quot;o&quot;, &quot;p&quot;, etc will only create confusion. Name then more generic, like oneStep, easy, etc.

Now let&#39;s talk about some redundant code.

    JPanel p = new JPanel();
    p.setBorder(BorderFactory.createLineBorder(Color.cyan));
    p.setSize(700,50);
    p.setVisible(true);
    p.setLayout(new FlowLayout());

There is no need to call JPanel&#39;s setVisible method because you will add it to the frame. Setting the size of the JPanel is kind-off redundant, cause the frame&#39;s layout manager will likely gonna ignore it.

    import javax.swing.*;
    import javax.swing.border.LineBorder;
